    },
    {
      "text": "A woman presented with dysphagia to solids for a month. On examination, there are multiple lesions on the lips. An endoscopy reveals obstructive lesions in the upper oesophagus. Which of the following additional findings can be seen in this patient?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 0,
          "text": "Development of GI polyps"
        },
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Degeneration of nitric oxide–producing neurons"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Iron deficiency anemia"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Apple core appearance on imaging"
        }
      ],
      "correct_choice_id": 2,
      "solution": "<p><strong>Correct Answer: C) Iron <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"209b85faf71692777185767d43e3bd\">deficiency</span> anemia</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Explanation:</strong></p>\n\n<p>This patient's condition is most likely suggestive of Plummer-Vinson syndrome, which is associated with iron <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"209b85faf71692777185767d43e3bd\">deficiency</span> anemia.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Plummer-Vinson Syndrome (Sideropenic Dysphagia)</strong></p>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Characterized by a <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1a0a43d74e16927772004473a05ae3\">triad</span> of:\n\t<ul>\n\t\t<li><strong>Iron-deficiency <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"53bee2a41216927771814d7ec3a67f\">anemia</span> </strong>(Sideropenia)</li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Atrophic glossitis</strong></li>\n\t\t<li><strong>Post- <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ba164bcd07169277718502f7ba3457\">Cricoid</span> Dysphagia </strong>(Upper <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"192677035a169277718780b4d6dbbb\">esophageal</span> webs)</li>\n\t</ul>\n\t</li>\n\t<li>Common in middle-aged women</li>\n\t<li>Increased risk of <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"5be0ee4ea316927771997104326685\">squamous</span> cell <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"988c19e3131692777183b6744d1920\">carcinoma</span> (pharynx and <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"bdbac654081692777196f9aab116f0\">proximal</span> esophagus)</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p><strong>Post <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"ba164bcd07169277718502f7ba3457\">cricoid</span> Dysphagia</strong> is caused by <strong>esophageal webs/rings</strong> in the upper <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"6a729a105a169277718788389dbeab\">esophagus</span> which leads to <span class=\"customMeta\" data-dictid=\"1788e0d4301692777199d457616bd4\">swallowing</span> difficulties.</p>\n\n<p><img alt=\"Esophageal Web Endoscopy\" data-author=\"Samir\" data-hash=\"5269\" data-license=\"CC BY SA 3.0\" data-source=\"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Esophageal_web.jpg\" data-tags=\"\" height=\"500\" src=\"https://image.prepladder.com/notes/SWkJIxoAaNfxxwPXF2Pf1743335797.png\" width=\"500\" /></p>\n\n<p> </p>",
